<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6355&amp;p=60836#p60836"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[8 tiles per row limit]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6355&amp;p=60836#p60836"><![CDATA[
It does have to be a fixed size, you can't write more than is possible to fit on the two nametables you have access to.<br /><br />But what is even more limited is the sprite system, which is what you were running into.  Despite being able to use 64 sprites total, you can only have 8 sprites per horizontal scan line.  Programmers get around this by alternating which sprite is shown on each screen refresh.  So for example, on the first frame you'd display "HELLO WOR  " and on the next you would have "  LLO WORLD".<br /><br />So that's an alternative to using the nametables...except that you really should get used to using them for text, that's essentially how you need to learn to do it. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3438">UncleSporky</a> — Mon May 03, 2010 12:59 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
