<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-05-03T12:18:27-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-05-03T12:18:27-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6355&amp;p=60828#p60828</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6355&amp;p=60828#p60828"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[8 tiles per row limit]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6355&amp;p=60828#p60828"><![CDATA[
Sprites are typically used to draw things that move around, such as the main character of a game. Since you can't put more than 8 of them side by side (like you observed), they are not suitable for writing text. The name tables should be used for that.<br /><br />The name tables are used to draw the background. They are grids of 32x30 tiles, the size of the NES screen. To draw tiles to the background you simply write to that grid the index of the tiles you want to display.<br /><br />Of course you'll have to worry about some details such as making sure that the name table you wrote to is the one being displayed (PPU register $2000 is used to select which name table is visible) and that this name table is aligned as you want (use the scroll register, $2005). To make sure the colors are correct you must also fill the corresponding attribute table accordingly.<br /><br />I'm guessing you learned how to draw sprites with a tutorial, is that correct? There are tutorials for the background too, so that's what you should be looking for in order to write text.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Mon May 03, 2010 12:18 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
